solution.p:
This complex fraction contains the simple fractions \dfrac{1}{2x},~ \dfrac{1}{x^2},~ \dfrac{1}{4} and \dfrac{1}{2x}. The LCD of these fractions is 4x^2.  We multiply the numerator and denominator of the complex fraction by 4x^2.  Doing this will not change the value of the fraction, but will clear all the "smaller" fractions inside. 
    \dfrac{\dfrac{1}{2x} - \dfrac{1}{x^2}}{\dfrac{1}{4} - \dfrac{1}{2x}} =\dfrac{\alert{4x^2}(\dfrac{1}{2x} - \dfrac{1}{x^2})}{\alert{4x^2}(\dfrac{1}{4} - \dfrac{1}{2x})}   
Then we apply the distributive law, so that we multiply each term of the numerator and each term of the denominator by \alert{4x^2}.
    \dfrac{\alert{4x^2}(\dfrac{1}{2x} - \dfrac{1}{x^2})}{\alert{4x^2}(\dfrac{1}{4} - \dfrac{1}{2x})}  = 
        \dfrac{\alert{\dfrac{4x^2}{1}} \cdot \dfrac{1}{2x} - \alert{\dfrac{4x^2}{1}} \cdot \dfrac{1}{x^2}}{\alert{\dfrac{4x^2}{1}} \cdot \dfrac{1}{4} - \alert{\dfrac{4x^2}{1}} \cdot \dfrac{1}{2x}}=\dfrac{2x-4}{x^2-2x}
Finally, we reduce the result to obtain
    \dfrac{2x-4}{x^2-2x} = \dfrac{2\cancel{(x-2)}}{x\cancel{(x-2)}} = \dfrac{2}{x}

statement.p:
Write each expression as a single algebraic fraction. 

x^{-1}-y^{-1}

(x^{-2}+y^{-2})^{-1}

li.p:
We write each power as a fraction, then simplify.
        x^{-1}-y^{-1} \amp = \dfrac{1}{x} - \dfrac{1}{y} \amp \amp \blert{\text{The LCD is}~xy.}
            \amp = \dfrac{1}{x} \cdot \dfrac{y}{y}- \dfrac{1}{y} \cdot \dfrac{x}{x}
            \amp = \dfrac{y-x}{xy}

We simplify the expression inside parentheses first.
        (x^{-2}+y^{-2})^{-1} \amp = (\dfrac{1}{x^2} + \dfrac{1}{y^2})^{-1} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Add fractions.}}
             \amp = (\dfrac{y^2+x^2}{x^2y^2})^{-1} = \dfrac{x^2y^2}{x^2+y^2}
    For the last step, remember that a negative exponent indicates the reciprocal of its base.

warning.p:
When working with fractions and exponents,it is important to avoid some tempting but incorrect algebraic operations.
In Example 3a, note that \dfrac{1}{x} - \dfrac{1}{y} 
e \dfrac{1}{x-y} For example, you can check that, for x=2 and y=3 , \dfrac{1}{2} - \dfrac{1}{3} 
e \dfrac{1}{2-3} = -1
In Example 3b, note that (x^{-2}+y^{-2})^{-1} 
e x^2+y^2 The fourth law of exponents does not apply to sums and differences; that is, (a+b)^n 
e a^n + b^n

solution.p:
If you said that the average speed is 50 miles per hour, you would be wrong!  Let's do some calculations.  Kathy's average speed for the round trip is given by
    \text{Average speed} = \dfrac{\text{Total distance}}{\text{Total time}}
The total distance she drove is 240 miles, but to find the total time we must compute the time Kathy drove on each part of the trip.  We use the formula d=rt and solve for t.

subsection.p:
The total distance traveled on the trip is d_1+d_2, and the total time required is  
    \dfrac{d_1}{r_1} + \dfrac{d_2}{r_2}
Thus, the average speed for the entire trip is
    \text{Average speed} = \dfrac{\text{Total distance}}{\text{Total time}} = \dfrac{d_1+d_2}{\dfrac{d_1}{r_1} + \dfrac{d_2}{r_2}}

Consider three improper fractions: \dfrac{8}{6},~ \dfrac{8}{4}, and \dfrac{8}{3}.  Can these fractions be simplified? 

We can reduce the first fraction: ~\dfrac{8}{6} = \dfrac{4}{3}  

The second fractrion reduces to a whole number:  `\dfrac{8}{4}  = \dfrac{2}{1} = 2 

The third fraction does not reduce, but by dividing the denominator into the numerator, we can write it as a whole number plus a proper fraction:  ~\dfrac{8}{3} = 2\dfrac{2}{3}

solution.p:
We divide 3x into each term of the numerator.
        \frac{9x^3 - 6x^2 + 4}{3x} \amp = \frac{9x^3}{3x}- \frac{6x^2}{3x}+ \frac{4}{3x}
            \amp = 3x^2 - 2x + \frac{4}{3x}
Note that the quotient is the sum of a polynomial, 3x^2 - 2x, and an algebraic fraction, \dfrac{4}{3x}.

subsection.p:
When using polynomial division, it helps to write the polynomials in descending powers of the variable. If the numerator is missing any terms, we can insert terms with zero coefficients so that like powers will be aligned. For example, to perform the division
    \dfrac{3x - 1 + 4x^3}{2x-1}
